com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.mq

Class MQHelper

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.mq.MQHelper

  • public class MQHelper
extends Object
    This class is intended to wrap behaviour needed to connect to and use MQSeries queues.

    Because we poll the MQSeries queue every second we get a message MQJE001: Completion Code 2, Reason 2033, which basically means there was nothing on the queue. There is no way of redirecting this output since they take it from System.err. See http://www-3.ibm.com/software/ts/mqseries/support/faqs/mqsfse.html#3 "Q: I keep getting the error "MQJE001: Completion Code 2, Reason 2033" on the DOS pane of the MQTester. What does this error mean? A: The 2033 'error' is really not an error, it is more of an MQSeries return status: MQRC_NO_MSG_AVAILABLE 2033 The MQTester program is polling a queue looking for a message, but there are no messages available." Message MQJE001 is a piece of debug which can't be turned off be any other means except by modifying the properties in the C:\Program Files\MQSeries\java\lib directory. By commenting out 39=MQJE001: Completion Code {0}, Reason {1} In the case of English: mqji.properties mqji_en_US.properties mqji_en.properties the entry becomes #39=MQJE001: Completion Code {0}, Reason {1} This in turn throws a java.util.MissingResourceException which can at least be caught unlike the System.err.println.

    Author:
    Dickon Field

      • setMQServerHostName

        public void setMQServerHostName(String hostName)
        This determines what type of connection will be used to the MQServer and queue manager. There are two types of connection to an MQServer:
        • bindings connection
        • client connection The bindings connection is to a server (and queue manager) on the same host as the application. It is faster, but obviously requires a complete MQ server installation on the same host as the app.
        The client connection is more flexible and is more likely to be used in a corporate environment where management issues predominate, but is implies greater latency since calls to MQ objects such as queue and queue manager require a conversation across the network using TCP/IP, while bindings connections may utilise platform-specific optimisations of this link.
        • To use the bindings connection set this property to null.
        • To use client connection set this property to the hostname (or IP address) or the host on which the MQ server hosting the queue manager to be used is installed, and specify at least a channel name.
        See documentation (Adapter_IBM_MQ.html) for more detailed explanation.
        Parameters:
        hostName - The TCP/IP address or hostname where the MQServer is running.

      • setMQServerPortNumber

        public void setMQServerPortNumber(int portNo)
        Set the port number that the MQServer is listening on. If no port number is specified (by not setting this property or setting it to 0 or a negative number) MQ will assume that the default should be used: 1414.

        Only used for client connections.

        Parameters:
        portNo - the port number

      • receive

        public MQMessage receive()
                  throws MQException
        Read a message and remove it from the queue. This is a blocking call which won't return until the read has succeeded or the wait interval has been reached.

        Same as calling receive(new MQMessage())

        Returns:
        the MQMessage retrieved from the queue.
        Throws:
        MQException - if there is a problem reading from the queue.
        See Also:
        receive(MQMessage), setWaitInterval(int)
